You are classifying the top-level sections of a non-fiction book by their structural role. This classification determines how aggressively each section will be compressed during distillation.

Classify each section as one of:
- "intro": Introduction, preface, prologue — sets up the book but mostly redundant with body chapters
- "body": Core argumentative chapters — the load-bearing content
- "conclusion": Conclusion, epilogue, afterword — recaps or extends body content
- "appendix": Appendix, reference tables, glossary — often the densest content, compress least
- "foreword": Foreword by someone else — compress heavily or skip
- "other": Acknowledgments, bibliography, index, about the author — compress heavily

Rules:
1. When in doubt, classify as "body" — it's the safest default.
2. A section titled "Introduction" that actually introduces novel frameworks should be "body", not "intro".
3. Look at the preview text to judge whether the section carries original argument or is setup/recap.

BOOK TITLE: {{ book_title }}

SECTIONS:
{% for section in sections %}
---
Section {{ loop.index }}: "{{ section.title }}"
Preview (first ~200 words):
{{ section.preview }}
---
{% endfor %}

Return a JSON array of objects, one per section, each with:
- "section_id": the section_id exactly as provided
- "title": the section title
- "section_type": one of "intro", "body", "conclusion", "appendix", "foreword", "other"

No preamble, no commentary. JSON array only.
